alternateDefinitions.categorical: An attribute who's value belongs to one out of multiple predefined groups.
alternateDefinitions.edge: Edges connect exactly two nodes in a network. Each edge can include additional information about the relationship between the two connected nodes. An edge can be onedirectional or bidirectional.
alternateDefinitions.hierarchy: A hierarchy is a special case of a network without cycles and with parent-child relationships. Each node has an arbitrary number of child nodes but exactly one parent node. Nodes without children are called leaf nodes. There exists exactly one "root" node which has no defined parent node.
alternateDefinitions.metadata: While data describes a real phenomenon, like measures in a physical experiment, metadata describes the data itself. It can for example provide information about the size of the dataset, sparseness of data entries, or information about the conditions under which the data was collected.
alternateDefinitions.natural language: A combination of a syntax and grammatical rules that govern how humans generally speak, read, or write.
alternateDefinitions.network: Network data can be described by a graph, which consists of nodes and edges.
alternateDefinitions.node: A node represents one item in a network. Every node can include additional information about the item. Nodes can be connected via edges.
alternateDefinitions.ordinal: An attribute who's value can be compared to other values of the same attribute  in a "greater" or "smaller" relationship. There is no exact distance defined between pairs of values.
alternateDefinitions.quantitative: An attribute that describes a numeric value associated with an item. Quantitative values, such as temperature or velocity, have a natural ordering, and a defined distance between each pair of elements.
alternateDefinitions.spatial: An item in spatial data has a position in a real or abstract space, defined by one or more quantified dimensions.
alternateDefinitions.supernode: A set of nodes that are grouped in such a way that a new supernode can replace and simplify the set and its connections. For example, known biological pathways are often grouped into supernodes to hide single unneeded complexity.
alternateDefinitions.volume: A region in three spatial dimensions, such as an object in the real world.

Our collaborators want to explore the extent of wildland fires over space and time, including how and where property boundaries are located across a wildland fire region. These regions define who owns which pieces of land and contain metadata about what kinds of privacy must be respected and what kinds of action are permissible. They also want to couple this with how far the properties are from active  areas of  the fire, the fire intensity, and where it might spread. By understanding these boundaries, they can plan how to distribute human resources, make decisions that minimize property loss, and act in ways to optimally combat and control the fire.
otherTypeExplanation:
Private--the data should be aggregated and shared in a way that respects privacy boundaries
Speculative/Predictive--the data should afford and integrate predictions for decision making

textualMisc:
High  throughput, noisy, & supplemental (e.g., social media)
Categorical labels (e.g., land owner names or qualitative assessments)

overallComments:
One challenge not addressed here is streaming temporality: when are we working with streaming and changing data, when are we using archival, and when might we see gaps where two agents are working with data from different timepoints (e.g., the data is stale due to the  changing environment). 

Looking forward to seeing the results!

As the data is stored in an RDF-based graph database, it is hard to map onto questions of size, items and attributes. The endpoint reports containing 107,584,675 triples, but not all of these are relevant for us; depending on the SPARQL query, the dataset can be restructured in many ways. As of now, our research group is focussed on a subset containing (319) diseases, (525) regions, their (7539) interconnections, and (224,229) sentences they co-occur in. These items contain categorical and quantitative values.
